04500nam a22006495i 9780823295579DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20211993nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232955797 a10.1515/97808232955792doi  a(DE-B1597)575262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aBIO0090002bisacsh1 aDrinker Bowen, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrancis Bacon :bThe Temper of a Man /cCatherine Drinker Bowen. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (245 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Dueling Ambitions -- tPROLOGUE. Lord Bacon's Reputation -- tI. An Elizabethan Eden 1561-1579 -- tII. The Struggle to Rise 1579-1613 -- t1. Two Conflicting Ambitions -- t2. Bacon and Essex -- t3. Bacon Begins to Write -- t4. The Ambition of the Understanding -- t5. The Ambition of the Will -- tIII. Bacon Ascending. A Time of Glory 1613-1620 -- t1. Lord Coke's Defeat -- t2. Lord Chancellor -- tIV. Impeachment 1621 -- tV. A Noble Five Years 1621-1626 -- tA Noble Five Years -- tAuthor's Note -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe portrait Bowen paints of this controversial man, Francis Bacon (1561-1626), balances the outward life and actions of Bacon with the seemingly contradictory aspects of his refined philosophical reflections. As Lord Chancellor of England, Bacon was impeached by Parliament for taking bribes in office, convicted and banished from London and the law courts. In a prayer Bacon composed during the interval following his punishment, he reveals that dichotomy of his existence was no more deeply felt than by himself, and he readily admits that his obligations to society were not as suited to his nature as the study of philosophy, science, and law.Modern scholars hold Bacon’s philosophical works, Novum Organum, Advancement of Learning, and The New Atlantis, as his greatest achievements. Bowen’s story reveals a man whose genius it was not to immerse himself in the rigor of scientific experimentation, but to realize what questions science should ask, and thereby reach beyond the status quo and appeal to the wider imagination of his generation. In his writings, Bacon challenged established social and religious orders, raised questions about the mind/body relation and the role of dreams, and foresaw the development of modern research university. It is Bacon’s legacy to have gone beyond his age and, out of pure intuition, anticipate the concerns of future generations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Philosophers.2bisacsh1 aBalestra, Dominic J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831107432960 cprintz978082321538640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329557940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295579/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK